Jewish media largely reflect Jewish preoccupations — and for the establishment, that is Israel and rising anti-Semitism.
“There is a perception that Jewish poverty is an oxymoron,” a communal professional told me.
“We don’t think of Jewish poverty as a priority story,” Andrew Silow-Carroll told me.
In the end, the priorities of Jewish media largely reflect the priorities of the Jewish community.
Community Jewish newspapers, dependent on their local federations for funding and readership, are urged to celebrate Jewish success, not highlight Jewish failure.